\begin_layout Section
Elasticity Concepts 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general problem is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\max\  & u\left(c,n\right)\\
 & \text{s.t.}\\
c & =wn+I & \lambda
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The FOCs are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u_{c} & =\lambda\\
u_{n} & =-\lambda w
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Combining gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\frac{u_{n}}{u_{c}}=w
\]

\end_inset

the standard 
\begin_inset Formula $MRS=w$
\end_inset

 case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting the budget constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $c=wn+I$
\end_inset

, the above becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-u_{n}\left(wn+I,n\right)=wu_{c}\left(wn+I,n\right)
\]

\end_inset

Totally differentiating yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
-u_{nc}\left(n+w\frac{\partial n}{\partial w}\right)-u_{nn}\frac{\partial n}{\partial w} & =u_{c}+w\left(u_{cc}\left(n+w\frac{\partial n}{\partial w}\right)+u_{cn}\frac{\partial n}{\partial w}\right)\\
\frac{\partial n}{\partial w}\left(-u_{nc}w-u_{nn}-w^{2}u_{cc}-wu_{cn}\right) & =u_{c}+wu_{cc}n+u_{nc}n\\
\frac{\partial n}{\partial w} & =-\frac{u_{c}+n\left(u_{nc}+wu_{cc}\right)}{u_{nn}+2wu_{nc}+w^{2}u_{cc}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The denominator is the second-order condition for the problem, which is
 negative in the case of a maximum.
 Thus, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial n}{\partial w}\propto u_{c}+n\left(u_{nc}+wu_{cc}\right)\label{eq:dndw}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The first term is the substitution effect, which is proportional to the
 marginal utility of consumption.
 The second is the income effect, which depends on the cross-utility (which
 determines how changes in consumption affect labor disutility), and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{cc}$
\end_inset

 which determines concavity of utility in consumption.
 The more concave, the faster 
\emph on
marginal
\emph default
 utility of consumption declines in wealth.
 
\end_layout

