\begin_layout Paragraph
Mechanical and Welfare Effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every taxpayer with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}>z^{*}$
\end_inset

 will pay an additional 
\begin_inset Formula $dzd\tau$
\end_inset

 in taxes.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is based on the fact that for small perturbations, we can treat the
 tax schedule as if it were linear.
 Thus, before they paid 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\left(z-z^{*}\right)$
\end_inset

, now they pay 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\tau+d\tau\right)\left(z-z^{*}\right)$
\end_inset

, the difference being 
\begin_inset Formula $dzd\tau$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The welfare losses from these additional tax receipts are valued according
 to the social marginal welfare weights 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the mechanical effect of this change on government revenue will be
 
\begin_inset Formula $dzd\tau$
\end_inset

, and the welfare 
\emph on
loss
\emph default
 will be 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(z\right)dzd\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the 
\emph on
net-of-welfare
\emph default
 mechanical gain is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=dzd\tau\int_{z^{*}}^{\infty}\left[1-g\left(z\right)\right]h\left(z\right)dz
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

 is the density of incomes induced by the tax policy.
 
\end_layout

